I think I know where you are coming from on the concept of &quot;African American&quot;,  &quot;Jewish Americans&quot;.  We were brought up in the &quot;melting pot&quot; story in New York State where so many immigrants to this country passed through, even  if they didn't stay actually settle in that state.  Barry, the Melting Pot theory was a history teacher's  lie/truth . . . wishing it so.  The best we can claim to have had was American stew.  A broth binding together chunks into a complete dish.   Lancaster, Pennsylvania is named after Lancaster in England.  New Netherlands a Dutch colony initially named for the country from whence those persons immigrated later became known as  New York after the Duke of York. Pennsylvania, Penns Woodlands was a haven for members of the Society of Friends (Quakers).  Almost every area has a Chinatown someplace.  There has been a Hasidic Jewish neighborhood in the New York City area for years and years and years. The orthodox Jewish people who live in that neighborhood do not push their religious philosophy on passerbys, but there would be no mistaking who they are  when you drove through their neighborhood by the distinctive way they dress.  So what is new when a group of Vietnamese who settle together because they understand each other label their area Little Saigon, and why get anymore upset about that than Lancaster, New Netherlands, Pennsylvania etc.<br>

